So basically you have to take on debt unless you come from money, had a decent job after undergrad which gave you the ability to save money, sneak non-academic jobs, or depend on handfuls of poorly paid academic side gigs

And typically, if you are awarded a Tri-Council or comparably large scholarship, you forfeit your departmental funding. Also, depending on the faculty, you’re not allowed to work any additional jobs. Someone I know was literally forced to quit a twice a week serving job.

For those who don’t know: that’s how much is offered per year for Tri-Council masters scholarships (federal funding) and is typical for department funding (give or take, the grad students in my last department only “got” $12,500/year. https://t.co/dOUzLTLs1b
Honestly, if I made $17,500 a year at the price that tuition, rent, and living expenses were 15+ years ago, I’d feel rich as hell

I can only dream of our funding even rising with inflation/tuition. Like when was the last time that graduate program stipends or Tri-Council scholarships increased? My prof who had NSERC during her masters 15 years ago said that her scholarship was the same as it is now. https://t.co/sLW8Ddj28o

@JohnThunderHea1 @DarrylLeroux I agree that it should be determined by the Métis Nation but then if that were the case, then First Nations would be excluded from exercising self-determination (since the Indian Act was conceptualized and is upheld by Canada rather than distinct Nations)
@JohnThunderHea1 @DarrylLeroux This would erase Inuit and (actual) Métis peoples because these groups aren't under the Indian Act

@johnforber23 @gleocbc @zakvescera However, it tends to entail having actual relations/connections with people from that group (unless the person was disconnected bc of the Sixties Scoop and residential school), and ppl whose last Indig ancestor was 4 generations ago typically don't have anyone to reconnect to

@johnforber23 @gleocbc @zakvescera That wasn't insinuated within what I noted as my short answer to your question. Indigenous Peoples have the right to self-determination, and bc there's many dif Indig groups/Nations, membership criteria differs from group to group

@johnforber23 @gleocbc @zakvescera Short answer: Métis don’t have Indian status (which is what I think you’re referring to, as “Indigenous” refers to First Nations, Métis, and Inuit in Canada). Indian status is a legal identity conceptualized/enforced by Canada and is distinct from each FN’s definition
It’s just the lack of humility in her response for me, though I guess I shouldn’t be surprised given that defensiveness and doubling-down is basically the pretendian playbook

This is assuming that an Indig ancestor anywhere in one’s genealogy means it’s chill to represent oneself as a member of that group. Like I have Swampy Cree and Saulteaux ancestors but don’t have any contemporary connections, so saying I’m either of those would be disingenuous
Or at least, that it’s acceptable for someone to claim an identity w/ no evidence so long as there is some distant ancestor that they shake out of the family tree after the fact?

“I do have [geneology] gaps, and it’s very likely that I maybe will be able to find a Tlingit ancestor somewhere. Maybe I will, maybe I won’t,” Bourassa said

There was a ton of media there and yet I can't find a recording from that presentation (tbh I didn't look that hard), but she also brings it up in the shared vid:
"I've been taught by my kookum, my grandmother, who is a Pipe Carrier and a traditional Elder...".

As other Indigenous peoples who have been disconnected as a consequence of colonialism likely feel, finding any information on your family is beyond exciting.  Just had to share because it's all I can think about.

Oral history transcripts by @gdins_org at https://t.co/NmkySFMTHt

3. I found out that my mom's youngest sibling has also reached out to the person I contacted to find family (whoa, neat!). My mom's going to try to contact her.

Oh, and my mom actually has 9 siblings (she thought that there were only 6) and I know their NAMES!
2.5 Anyhow, finding that transcript was AMAZING. Most of what I have is factual details -- marriage certificates, obituaries, Métis Scrip documents -- but few stories.

2.4 The interviewer asks: "Was it right to steal all those
things?"

Octave: "That was his [John Williams'] own horse. He didn't steal them because that was his own horses."

Long story short, they came back with a team of horses.

2.3 For their horses, they travelled to Saskatoon. "All the policemen and soldiers was there". 

Delorme said to them: "By God, I bought that horse and I like to see the man who would take that horse from me." 

This was recently after Delorme had been shot at Batoche. Badass™.

2.2 Because the gov took everything, John William and his brother-in-law, Joseph Delorme, decided to get their things (especially their horses) back. 

For their things, they raided Fort Carlton at night and dispersed items to other Métis who also had all their possessions stolen

2.1 Found a @gdins_org oral history transcript of my GG uncle Octave Fiddler (recounting stories from his father/my GG grand-father, John William Fiddler). He said that when the government came, they took everything. 

"They come and clean everything up. Not a spoon or a knife."
